{"ts":"2026-06-26T21:58:23.663Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing the Hero Section**\n\nOkay, the `InnerPageHero` component is looking great! I've confirmed it handles centered and normal layouts with a premium-looking SVG animation. My next step is to build the interactive marketplace at `/app/build/marketplace/page.tsx`.\n\n\n**Refining the Marketplace Page**\n\nI've decided to build the `/app/build/marketplace/page.tsx` as a fully self-contained client component. This design choice aims to streamline compilation, referencing, and editing for the marketplace. Now, I'm defining the filters. I've got the industry, function, maturity stage, and platform filters mapped out. Next up is keyword search.\n\n\n**Crafting the Marketplace Filters**\n\nI'm moving forward with a custom filter UI for the marketplace. The aim is a visually engaging and intuitive experience, avoiding the clutter of standard dropdowns. I'm leaning toward a modern grid of parameters with clear labels and subtle borders, or customized select menus with Lucide icons. A prominent search bar with a glowing icon will be included, and a \"Reset Filters\" button will appear dynamically. I'm also planning the agent category tabs as premium capsules.\n\n\n**Designing Agent Cards**\n\nI'm now focusing on the layout of a single agent card to maximize its visual appeal. I'm aiming for a premium feel with custom glowing borders using Tailwind transitions. The agent's category, e.g., \"Garage,\" will be clearly displayed with a color-coded gradient badge. We're experimenting with a bold, transition-on-hover blueprint name, a use case section featuring italicized quotes, and a digestible description. Finally, I'm integrating \"Related Capabilities\" tags and an interactive \"Add to Compare\" button in a dedicated action row.\n\n\n**Finalizing Agent Card CTAs**\n\nI'm finalizing the interactive elements on the agent cards. I'm focusing on the CTAs, with options like \"Deploy to Sandbox\" and \"Talk to Agent\". I'm planning to make the interaction feel dynamic, possibly using an interactive simulator directly within the card, showing a mini console when users click a CTA, that streams simulated output. The simulator will greatly enhance user engagement.\n\n\n**Enhancing the Sandbox CTA**\n\nI'm now implementing the \"Deploy to Sandbox\" CTA. My goal is to make it interactive and dynamic. When a user clicks, I want a simulated console to load right within the agent card, displaying realistic progress logs and an area for test queries, offering a truly premium and engaging experience. This interactive simulator should greatly enhance user engagement, I think!\n\n\n**Developing the Comparison Feature**\n\nI'm now focusing on a powerful agent comparison feature. I'm visualizing connection wires or visual dots between agent cards in a comparison view. I'll include the \"Analyze Comparison\" CTA. When a user clicks, a dynamic modal overlay expands to reveal a detailed comparison matrix. This will feature name, category, and specifications such as GFF fit, use case, related capabilities, execution DAG, safety prompts, datasources, and performance metrics in a side-by-side view. The final result should look sleek and professional!\n\n\n**Verifying Necessary Imports**\n\nI'm now focusing on import organization and path verification within the marketplace page. I need these: icons from `lucide-react`, React hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useMemo`, `useRef`), the `Link` component, and our components like `InnerPageShell` and `InnerPageHero`. I verified the path and current imports of `app/build/marketplace/page.tsx` for proper setup.\n\n\n**Designing the Sandbox Simulator**\n\nI'm now fully focused on the \"Deploy to Sandbox\" interaction. I envision a sleek modal with a terminal-style console displaying a step-by-step loading animation. This will create a dynamic and premium experience, loading the container enclave, binding context, mounting safety shields, opening data connectors, and injecting the core system. The user will be instantly engaged.\n\n\n**Simulating User Interactions**\n\nI'm now integrating interactive prompts into the sandbox simulator. After the console loads, I'll add a prompt input for user queries. I'll include two pre-set test prompts specific to each agent, which will show a typing status and stream a highly realistic and premium response matching agent safety directives. This will greatly enhance the user engagement. This is all 100% frontend-only.\n\n\n**Analyzing Policy Compliance**\n\nI've been analyzing the remote work policy, and how it impacts offshore contractors. I've confirmed that remote work on customer data cores is prohibited. Offshore developers must use air-gapped instances for their code pipelines. The search, based on sovereign compliance standards, found a clear HR policy section.\n\n\n**Designing the Interaction Flow**\n\nI'm now designing the interaction flow for the \"Talk to Agent\" CTA. My focus is on creating a premium chat drawer or modal. The agent will introduce itself, confirming compliance with local guidelines, and its context window. I want to make the chat feel very intuitive and easy to use. I'm exploring different ways to show how the user can select their options.\n\n\n**Refining the Interaction Designs**\n\nI'm now iterating on the \"Talk to Agent\" CTA interaction. I'm focusing on a modern chat interface, possibly a drawer or modal, where the agent introduces itself and confirms compliance. I'm aiming for an intuitive design, showing how the user can select options. I'm also planning preset architecture questions, and how they provide detailed responses.\n\n\n\n**Implementing the Agent Marketplace**\n\nI'm now implementing the agent marketplace design. I've got a search bar with a \"Search certified agent blueprints\" placeholder and a search icon. I'm focusing on the filter tags, including glowing effects. I am also working on the category list with instant filtering on tab clicks. The card layout is designed with hover borders that glow, and a use case styled like a quote.\n\n\n\n**Constructing the Comparison Modal**\n\nI'm now designing the comparison modal in full detail. The modal will prominently display the technical comparison matrix, featuring an in-depth side-by-side view. I'm visualizing the modal's layout, where it will compare aspects like use case, GFF fit, capabilities, system prompts, and diagrams. I will emphasize the three foundational security layers: Context Boundary Spec, Safety Shields, and Cryptographic Integrations.\n\n\n**Defining Data Structures**\n\nI'm now defining the `AgentBlueprint` interface, ensuring it includes `id`, `name`, `category`, `description`, and essential fields like `useCase`, `gffFit`, `relatedCapabilities`, and filters. I've also incorporated `sandboxResponse` for preset prompts and answers. The data structure will guide the blueprint filtering, with the necessary fields for a dynamic marketplace experience.\n\n```typescript\ninterface AgentBlueprint {\n  id: string;\n  name: string;\n  category: string;\n  desc: string;\n  useCase: string;\n  gffFit: \"Garage\" | \"Foundry\" | \"Factory\";\n  relatedCapabilities: string[];\n  industry: string;\n  function: string;\n  maturityStage: string;\n  platformFit: string;\n  schema: string;\n  stages: string[];\n  datasources: string;\n  perfMetric: string;\n  systemPrompt: string;\n  sandboxResponse: {\n    prompt: string;\n    answer: string;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n\n**Mapping Blueprint Filters**\n\nI'm now mapping the agent blueprints to the specified filters. I need to ensure perfect alignment between the sixteen blueprints and their properties like category, industry, function, maturity stage, and platform fit. I am writing a comprehensive file at `/app/build/marketplace/page.tsx` that includes all imports.\n\n\n"}}
